text: Not a bad idea.
My buddy turned his whole collection into Duals.
We started the massive buylist on our monster. $500 is $1068 before grading, and we still haven't found the 3x Cavern of Souls hiding in the collection.
They're really close to mint, so we'll probably sell them on Facebook.
Then we have to sell these boxes of bulk or "instant collections" for $10 a pop and we're golden.
All parts of the buffalo :)
I actually passed that line along to the people who went in on the collection with me.

Once we get our money for the flip we're going to talk to the wife of the guy who wanted 8k for his collection. Her eyes lit up at the mention of $500. If we offer $1k cash she might be able to sway him. We'll see.
Dean have you by chance read the book Loose Balls?
I haven't.
What's it about?
It’s worth even if you’re not a sports guy. It’s about the ABA in the 70’s, the basketball league that tried to compete w the NBA
Anyway there’s a great chapter in it about how they were gonna try and sign Kareem Abdul-Jabar before the NBA could because they figured just seeing a cash offer would make his eyes pop
Of course being the ABA they fucked it up and tried to lowball him and the rest is history
So yeah sometimes just making that cash offer is the right play
(I don't know the history. Did he accept?)
No because their guy making the offer changed it without telling anyone thinking he could pocket the difference
Ahhh
I opened the offer at $500 and he balked. Hard. I'm hoping to play them off each other a bit.
I'm pretty sure I would lose money if I bought the collection at half his valuation.
Maybe. It's possible I'd break even, but I don't think it's likely.
My point being, he thinks I lowballed him.
They also forgot to buy a trophy for their first championship and had to send a ref to radio shack in the third quarter where he bought a radio for the players to share as their trophy
...wow
The book is nuts. The 70’s man. It’s all dudes on coke making decisions they shouldn’t be making
Yeah, 70s guys on coke made way for the 80s and early 90s Wallstreet guys on coke that fucked everyone over.
So...thanks, coke.
Yea, the guy I got the collection from last weekend was pretty set on his TCG market price until I took out some $100 bills and said he could have his money today.
It’s a real thing
Yeah, how do you do that casually?
How much more is the cash worth today than maybe having a little more down the road
I'd feel super cheesy. I really wanted to flash money at the $8k couple.
But I wasn't sure how.

When people stand by their asking price I’ve just been telling people some sort of “you can pursue that price and put in the work to see via that outlet. After fees, your own shipping, time etc, you’ll have sold it for $3 more. Or here’s some cash today to have it out of your house today”
Some sort of message like that usually gets across to most folks
And do you pull out the money at that point, or just drop that line?
I do when they know my offer and they think it’s not enough. Seeing X dollars in person as opposed to the number in their head makes t a little more real

"I'll offer you $50." 
"No, that's too low." 
"Okay, but here's $50 cash, live and in person." 
"oh shit, okay, sounds like a deal!"
Kinda like that?

text: Wow, yeah, that's a killing
Yeah.
Holy shit. Buying this collection was the best financial decision I ever made.
He priced out 17 cards on the first two pages of this large binder, got bored, gave up and listed the whole thing for four hundred bucks. I just made Bank.
Lol
I didn't even want to look past the first three pages I just stopped and said yeah sure his four hundred bucks I'll take the whole thing thanks.
Meanwhile letgo near me is people selling one binder page at a time for $10
After I left the collection he goes yeah there's probably some good stuff in there I like to play vintage and Legacy.
What a jackass
Dean, shoot me a list of the cool shit you find
Nice that’s awesome Dean
I found a KCI, Tarmogoyf and Aluren in his bulk.
Jason, not a jackass, just a real casual.
He didn't have any legacy/vintage straps you'd expect, really.
Also, there was a City of Traitors from Exodus.

He'd been playing "off and on for the last 15 years" and it showed. Very fascinating connection. A bunch of Rhystic Studies. Some old Un stuff. Drips and drabs of good stuff from a lot of Magic's history
I'll post some pics tomorrow
Hell yes
